==English==
=== Etymology ===
{{OF.}} ''[[prosperer]]'', from {{L.}} ''[[prosperare]]'', to cause to succeed, from ''[[prosperus]]'', favorable, from [[Old Latin]] ''pro spere'', according to expectation, from ''[[pro#Latin|pro]]'', for, and ''[[spes]]'', hope<!--not a portmanteau-->

=== Adjective ===
{{en-adj-more}}

#[[characterize]]d by [[success]]
#:''Trading Babe Ruth was far more '''prosperous''' for the Yankees than for the Red Sox.''
#well off; [[affluent]]
#:''he was raised in a very '''prosperous''' household''
#[[favorable]]
#:''he chose a '''prosperous''' lottery number that evening''

====Synonyms====
*(''characterized by success''): [[successful]]
*(''well off''): [[affluent]], [[rich]], [[well off]], [[well-to-do]]
*(''favorable''): [[favorable]]

